At first I thought it was the disk player, so I tried it on a different system and it did the same thing.  I was extremely disappointed as this was a gift for my father.  He is disabled and the only enjoyment he gets would be from listening to the radio and/or watching TV.  Verfy disappointed.

Avoid this.  It's very poorly mastered and transferred.  Audio quality is very lacking.  The picture has a good deal of jutter, and very little effort was done not only to remaster/clean up the originals, but just to do basics like luminescence balance.  Some scenes are so dark and muddy you can't make out Red's face.  Or cropping (some scenes have a 5-10% black strip on more than one side, or show the edge of the original filmstock--that's an easy fix that just shows the laxity and shoddiness of the digital producers).  I also don't like how they replaced his original music with a silly banjo tune.  I understand why they did (content licensing), but it really does detract from the Red Skelton experience.  The DVDs are also mastered at very low quality, and a good deal of digital noise and compression artifacting shows up.  Really poor job.  Not worth even the little money I paid for it.  Spring for the more expensive TIME-licensed collections.  It's worth it.
